{
  "doc_id": "22743",
  "text": "The surface morphology of the BC adsorbent is shown in Figure 2 . The BC presents an irregular and disorganized mesoporous structure without very well-defined pores. By increasing 5000 times (Figure 2(c) ) it is possible to observe the pores where the adsorption process takes place. This result is in agreement with those observed by previous works [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Figure 3 shows the X-ray diffraction profile of BC. The BC is a mixed adsorbent in which the carbon is distributed along a porous structure of hydroxyapatite (Ca10(PO4)6(OH)2). The crystalline species of BC was identified by comparing the characteristic peaks shown using the database of the diffractometer available in the Journal of Crystallographic Powder Diffraction. The peaks can be observed at 26 , 32 , 40 , 46.8 , and 49.6 , which correspond to (002), (211), (310), (222), and (213) Miller planes. According to [CITATION_3] and [CITATION_4] these peaks confirm the calcium hydroxyapatite structure of BC. Furthermore, the crystallite size values were calculated by the Scherrer's equation, taking the most intense peak and the Gaussian model. The crystallite size of BC is 4.97 nm. The FT-IR spectrum was conducted to determine the functional groups of the material. The FT-IR analysis of BC was presented in Figure 4 and it can be noted that the results agree with information obtained by XRD patterns, where the characteristic peaks of hydroxyapatite are evident. The OH stretching vibration appearing at 3300-3450 cm À1 was attributed to the presence of phenols, alcohols, and carboxylic group. Also, the fact that this band is wide may be due to the presence of adsorbed water [CITATION_5] . The C = O and C = C stretching vibrations of protein and collagen on bovine bone are present in the 1500-1600 cm À1 range [CITATION_6] . The bands at 1448-1415 cm À1 are due to the C-O stretching and has been assigned to CO 3 À2 group, while the signals at 565, 603, 1030, and 2010 cm À1 are characteristics of stretching and bending vibrations of PO 4 3À groups [CITATION_7] Delgadillo-Velosco et al., 2017; [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . ",
